        "text": "In a powerful November 1 Instagram post, Solange Knowles shared that she separated from her husband, Alan Ferguson earlier this year.\n\nShe wrote, \"11 years ago i met a phenomenal man who changed every existence of my life. this year we separated and parted ways.\"\n\nIn an Instagram post, songstress Solange Knowles opened up to her followers, revealing in a lengthy caption that she and her husband of five years, music video director Alan Ferguson, separated in early 2019.\n\n\"11 years ago i met a phenomenal man who changed every existence of my life,\" Knowles wrote, \"early this year we separated and parted ways, (and tho it ainâ€™t nan no body business ðŸ˜­) i find it necessary to protect the sacredness of my personal truth and to live in it fully just as I have before and will continue to do. it is unfair to not have power of your own story as you shape and mold and rewrite it yourself.\"\n\nThe \"When I Get Home\" singer, who married Ferguson in New Orleans in 2014 (her sister BeyoncÃ© and niece Blue Ivy were in attendance) revealed in 2017 that she'd been treating an unnamed \"Autonomic Disorder.\" In her post, Knowles seemed to allude to her health struggles as an impetus to open up to her fans.\n\n\"the past 2 years have brought me more physical and spiritual transition and evolution than ever before,\" she wrote. \"My body left me with no choice but to listen and be still within that stillness i begin my journey in confronting my worst enemy, fear. ive [sic] lived my best and worst moments in front of the lens and gaze of the world since i was a teenager. ive always tried to live in my truth no matter how ugly or full of love it is. ive also tried to carve out the space to protect my heart, and my life as it unfolds, evolves, and changes.\"\n\nKnowles has a 15-year-old son, Julez, from her first marriage, while she and Ferguson didn't have children. But despite the news, the star closed out her statement with a message of positivity.\n\n\"It is unfair to not have power of your own story as you shape and mold and rewrite it yourself. a n***a ainâ€™t perfect, but im leaning into the fear of the unknown and all the glory and power i know exist within god and the universes grace. may all of your transitions no matter how big or small, be kind to you and filled with incredible love and light!\""
